I am not sure what exactly is confusing you so here is some other way how you can look at your example.

---

    J j = Test::foo;

can be rewritten as 

    J j = () -&gt; Test.foo();

since it provides body to `m()` method from `J` functional interface and that method doesn&#39;t require any arguments (which is why it starts with `() -&gt;`). 

But that can be seen as shorter version of 

    J j = new J(){
        public void m(){
            Test.foo(); //correct despite `foo` returning value    
        }
    };

which is correct, because Java allows us to ignore returned value of called method like in case of [`List#add(E element)`][1] which returns `boolean` value, but we still are allowed to write code like `list.add(1)` without having to handle returned value.


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/java.base/java/util/List.html#add(E)

